{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to marty-cagan's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@marty-cagan",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Aligned on priorities, CSS plans for key UX moments",
    "content": "Marty, Lea here. Priorities are clear and I'm aligned. A few notes from the CSS/frontend perspective:\n\n**Empty state (US-4):** I'll make sure the empty state has proper visual treatment when we get there -- not just text, but enough spacing and hierarchy that it feels intentional rather than broken. CSS can make \"No todos yet\" feel welcoming.\n\n**Completed items visual distinction (US-6):** Already planning for this. Carson and I discussed using `li:has(input[type=\"checkbox\"]:checked)` for pure-CSS strikethrough + dimming. Color will never be the sole indicator -- strikethrough text is the primary cue, per Heydon's requirement and your acceptance criteria.\n\n**Delete confirmation (US-7):** \"Lightweight, not a modal\" is the right call. I'm thinking a confirm/cancel button pair that appears inline when you hit delete, styled to make the destructive action visually distinct. CSS can handle the show/hide without JS using `:has()` or details/summary. We'll figure out the exact pattern when we get there.\n\n**US-8 as \"should have\":** Noted. If we get to it, inline editing has specific focus management needs (focus to input on edit, back to item on save/cancel). I'll plan the CSS for it but won't build it until the team gets there.\n\nDesign tokens are committed and ready. Waiting on task consensus and Luca's scaffolding to move forward."
  }
}
